{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617540"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16472"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16472"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.07,0.24,0.46,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70412"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9163"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7180"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"10346"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"},{"type":"tags","id":"10921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21761"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70412"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-week history of headache, low-grade fever, and neck stiffness. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He recently migrated from Southeast Asia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. He has mild neck stiffness but no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECerebrospinal fluid analysis reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOpening pressure: elevated\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAppearance: clear with fibrin web formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 500 x 10^6/L (predominantly mononuclear cells)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProtein: 3.0 g/L (0.15-0.45)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGlucose: 1.8 mmol/L (2.2-3.9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGram stain: no organisms seen\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Group A Streptococcus","Cryptococcus neoformans","Epstein-Barr virus","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Treponema pallidum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and CSF findings are highly suggestive of tuberculous meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a chronic meningitis characterised by a lymphocytic pleocytosis, markedly elevated protein, low glucose, and the characteristic finding of fibrin web formation. The patient\u0027s background of recent migration from Southeast Asia, where tuberculosis is endemic, adds support to this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGroup A Streptococcus\u003C/strong\u003E causes acute bacterial meningitis with a predominantly neutrophilic pleocytosis, typically much higher cell counts, and would be visible on Gram stain. The clinical course would be more acute and severe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/strong\u003E can cause chronic meningitis, particularly in immunocompromised patients. While it can present similarly, cryptococcal infection typically has a less marked inflammatory response and would be visible on India ink stain or detected by cryptococcal antigen testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause aseptic meningitis but typically presents with a more acute course and less severe CSF abnormalities. The protein elevation would not typically be as high, and fibrin webs would not be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/strong\u003E (neurosyphilis) can cause chronic meningitis but typically presents with more prominent neurological symptoms and would be associated with positive syphilis serology. The CSF protein elevation is usually less marked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of tuberculous meningitis can be challenging as acid-fast bacilli are often not seen on microscopy, and culture can take several weeks. Treatment should not be delayed while awaiting confirmatory tests if clinical suspicion is high, as delays in treatment are associated with poor outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic meningitis with elevated protein, lymphocytic pleocytosis, and fibrin web formation is characteristic of tuberculous meningitis.","CSF analysis showing predominantly mononuclear cells suggests a chronic or viral meningitis rather than acute bacterial infection.","The presence of fibrin webs in CSF is highly suggestive of tuberculous meningitis."],"references":["Hoffman O, Weber RJ. Pathophysiology and treatment of bacterial meningitis. Ther Adv Neurol Disord. 2009 Nov;2(6):1-7. doi: 10.1177/1756285609337975. PMID: 21180625; PMCID: PMC3002609.","Manyelo CM, Solomons RS, Walzl G, Chegou NN. Tuberculous Meningitis: Pathogenesis, Immune Responses, Diagnostic Challenges, and the Potential of Biomarker-Based Approaches. J Clin Microbiol. 2021 Feb 18;59(3):e01771-20. doi: 10.1128/JCM.01771-20. PMID: 33087432; PMCID: PMC8106718.","Chin JH. Tuberculous meningitis: Diagnostic and therapeutic challenges. Neurol Clin Pract. 2014 Jun;4(3):199-205. doi: 10.1212/CPJ.0000000000000023. PMID: 25110618; PMCID: PMC4121465.","Marx GE, Chan ED. Tuberculous meningitis: diagnosis and treatment overview. Tuberc Res Treat. 2011;2011:798764. doi: 10.1155/2011/798764. Epub 2011 Dec 21. PMID: 22567269; PMCID: PMC3335590."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16472"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T22:53:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T22:55:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9163"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70412"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links